We begin by determining the two ratios from the provided statements.

Step 1. Calculate Debt to Asset Ratio.
 • Total Liabilities come from the balance sheet. In this problem the only liabilities given are current liabilities:
  – Accounts Payable = 1,240,000.00
  – Taxes Payable = 253,246.99
  – Total Current Liabilities = 1,493,246.99  
 • Total Assets (ending) = 15,200,446.16  
 • Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets  
  = 1,493,246.99 / 15,200,446.16 ≈ 0.0983  
 Rounded to two decimals, we report this as 0.10.

Step 2. Calculate Operating Cash Flow to Net Income Ratio.
 • From the cash flow statement, Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –64,099.10  
 • From the income statement, Net Profit = 707,199.17  
 • Operating Cash Flow to Net Income Ratio = (Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities) / (Net Profit)  
  = –64,099.10 / 707,199.17 ≈ –0.0906  
 Rounded to two decimals, this ratio is –0.09.

Thus, the final answer is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.10",
    "Operating Cash Flow to Net Income Ratio": "-0.09"
  }
}
